[`Array.prototype.reduce`](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/JavaScript/Reference/Global_Objects/Array/Reduce) accepts a function whose return value is eventually returned from `reduce` itself. The function is passed each element of the array, along with the value accumulated so far. For example,
```js
[1, 2, 3].reduce((accumulator, element) =&gt; accumulator + element)
// =&gt; 6
```
You can also provide an initial value, which will be passed to your function as `accumulator` on the first iteration.

At a basic level, to count how many occurrences of an object with a certain property with `reduce`, you could use something like this,
```js
let array = [
  { foo: 4 },
  { foo: 6 },
  { bar: 8 },
]

array.reduce((count, element) =&gt; {
  if (element.foo !== undefined) {
    return count + 1
  } else {
    return count
  }
}, 0)
// =&gt; 2
```
